We have fields in an object, not parameters. I think we should allow documenting like this only for functions.
For objects, if someone wants to add deprecated docs for a field, shouldn't the following (documenting at field level) work and be enough?
# The `Object2` is a user-defined object.
# 
# + fieldTwo - This is the description of the `Object2`'s `fieldTwo` field.
public type Object2 object {

    # This is the description of the `Object2`'s `fieldOne` field.
    # # Deprecated
    # deprecated docs
    @deprecated
    public string fieldOne = "Foo";

    # This is the description of the `Object2`'s `t` field.
    # # Deprecated
    # deprecated docs
    @deprecated
    TYPE1 t = CONST3;

    public string fieldTwo = "";

    public function doThatOnObject(string paramOne, TYPE1 t) {
        self.fieldOne = paramOne;
        self.t = t;
    }
};

const string CONST3 = "CONST3";
const string CONST4 = "CONST4";

public type TYPE1 CONST3|CONST4;
Currently says
error: .::xyz.bal:6:5: constructs annotated as '@deprecated' must have 'Deprecated' documentation
error: .::xyz.bal:12:5: constructs annotated as '@deprecated' must have 'Deprecated' documentation

